AGI - A high official of Hamas accused Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu> of reporting to the starting point the negotiations for the release of Israeli hostages held in Gaza. Haaretz writes it. The official told the Qatari newspaper The New Arab that Netanyahu did this to earn time. "The hostage families must know that the last round of negotiations is the last chance to bring back their children," warned the official.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2 US Secretary of Defense Austin confirms: "in pause supply of weapons to Israel"</h2>
U.S. Secretary of Defense Lloyd Austin is the first U.S. high official to publicly confirm that he has paused a transfer of arms to Israel > for concerns related to the military operation in Rafah, writes Haaretz. "We are currently reviewing some short-term security aid. In the context of current events in Rafah". He told a senate committee. Austin said that the United States was clear from the outset that Israel must account for civilians in Rafah.&nbsp;
<h2>Oms, hospitals in southern Gaza have fuel for three days
The southern hospitals of the Gaza Strip have only three days of fuel > said the head of the World Health Organization (Oms), > because of the closure of border crossings in Rafah>. Despite international objections, yesterday Israel sent the tanks to the overcrowded southern city of Rafah and closed the nearby crossing with Egypt, which is the main access channel for aid to the Palestinian territory besieged. "The closure of the border crossing continues to prevent the United Nations from carrying fuel. Without fuel, all humanitarian operations will stop. The closure of the border also prevents the delivery of humanitarian aid to Gaza," says General Manager, Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus on X. "The hospitals in southern Gaza have only three days of fuel, which means that the services could soon stop." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Hamas: new common pit in Al-Shifa, exhumed 49 bodies</h2>
The Hamas> government in the Gaza Strip has identified a new common pit > from which 49 bodies have already been exhumed in the Al Shifa hospital. The authorities of Gaza state that rescue teams continue to dissuade the bodies and expect to find "new bodies" in the common pit, the third found in the hospital center from which about 400 deaths have already been recovered, according to a statement. During operations at the hospital, Israel claimed to have killed some 200 alleged militants and questioned more than 800 suspects, including identifying about 500 members of Hamas and Palestinian Islamic Jihad, including senior officials. So far, according to Hamas, seven common pits were found in the Gaza Strip hospitals, three of which in Naser, three Khan Yunis (south) and another in the Kamal Adwan hospital (north).
