The disposal of repairable products is a serious threat to the environment and every year generates 35 million tonnes of waste in the European Union. This is what we read on the website &nbsp;https://www.europarl.europa.eu/ from news of the work of the European Parliament.&nbsp;</span>
With the "right to repair", the European Union takes another step towards achieving a circular economy model within 2050 within the framework of the European Green Pact, the EU's roadmap to reach climate neutrality for 2050.
&nbsp;
In April 2024 Parliament approved the reform of the regulation on the so-called "right to repair" which aims to strengthen the right to repair. The project of this provision aims to encourage more sustainable consumption, facilitating the repair of defective goods, reducing waste and supporting the repair industry. Parliament's rapporteur, René Repasi (S&amp;D, DE), said: "The right to repair for consumers finally becomes reality. Repairing the products will be easier and cheaper than buying new more expensive products. This is an important milestone for Parliament and demonstrates its commitment to support consumers in combating climate change."
&nbsp;
<h2> Why repair is better
&nbsp;
According to a Eurobarometer 2020 survey, 77% of EU consumers would prefer to repair their goods rather than buy new ones, but then end up replacing them or discarding them due to the high repair costs and lack of services provided.
&nbsp;
Another obstacle to more sustainable consumption is obsolescence: some products are designed to spoil after a certain time of use. In some cases, the components of the devices are assembled in such a way that they cannot be removed and replaced.
&nbsp;
Electronics is the source of waste that grows faster in the EU.
&nbsp;
Electronic device repairs would be beneficial for the environment, leading to a reduction in the use of resources, lower greenhouse gas emissions and lower energy consumption.
